RAID basics, and quotas.

RAID, a redundant array of independent disks, combines several physical disks into one logical device, to get redundancy, performance, or both. Linux does software RAID through a tool called mdadm, using the kernel's md subsystem, so you don't need any special hardware RAID controller.

Let's go through the common levels. RAID zero, striping, splits data across the disks; it's the fastest, but it survives nothing, one disk dies and all your data is gone. RAID one, mirroring, keeps an identical copy on every disk; it survives up to all-but-one disk failing. RAID five is striping plus one parity block, needs at least three disks, and survives a single disk failure. RAID six is striping plus two parity blocks, needs at least four disks, and survives two failures. And RAID ten combines mirroring and striping for the best blend of speed and safety. As for picking one: RAID one is the simplest redundancy, great for boot drives; RAID ten is the go-to default when you care about performance and reliability; and prefer RAID six over RAID five on big modern disks, because RAID five rebuilds are slow and risky on large drives.

Now the single most important thing in this section: RAID is not a backup. RAID protects you against a disk failing. It does absolutely nothing against rm dash-r-f, against ransomware, against fire or theft, or against filesystem corruption, because all of those happily replicate to every disk in the array instantly. So always run separate, real backups, in addition to RAID.

For the commands: sudo mdadm dash-dash-create makes an array, where you give it the level and the member disks. Once created, the array is a single block device, slash-dev-md-zero, that you format and mount like any other. You check status with cat slash-proc-mdstat, and get detail with mdadm dash-dash-detail. When a disk fails, you mark it with dash-dash-fail, remove it with dash-dash-remove, and add a replacement with dash-dash-add, then watch the rebuild in proc-mdstat.

Finally, quotas, briefly. Quotas cap how much space, or how many files, a given user or group may use on a filesystem, which is handy on shared servers. You enable them by adding usrquota to the mount options in fstab, initialise the databases with quotacheck and quotaon, set a user's limits with edquota dash-u, where a soft limit is a warning with a grace period and a hard limit is an absolute ceiling, and you report on usage with repquota dash-a. On XFS it works a little differently, through the uquota mount option and the xfs-underscore-quota tool, but the concepts are identical. And that completes the storage stack, from physical disk all the way up to per-user limits.
